M|vercel-react-best-practices|When to use this pattern:
M|vercel-react-best-practices|- Loading fonts for OG image generation
M|vercel-react-best-practices|- Loading static logos, icons, or watermarks
M|vercel-react-best-practices|- Reading cfg files that don't change at runtime
M|vercel-react-best-practices|- Loading email templates or other static templates
M|vercel-react-best-practices|- Any static asset that's the same across all requests
M|vercel-react-best-practices|When not to use this pattern:
M|vercel-react-best-practices|- Assets that vary per request or user
M|vercel-react-best-practices|- Files that may change during runtime (use caching with TTL instead)
M|vercel-react-best-practices|- Large files that would consume too much mem if kept loaded
M|vercel-react-best-practices|- Sensitive data that shouldn't persist in mem
M|vercel-react-best-practices|With Vercel's [Fluid Compute](https://vercel.com/docs/fluid-compute), module-level caching is especially effective because multiple concurrent requests share the same function instance. The static ass
M|vercel-react-best-practices|In traditional serverless, each cold start re-executes module-level code, but subsequent warm invocations reuse the loaded assets until the instance is recycled.
